# Vagrant Development Workflow

## Common Commands
- `vagrant up` - Start a VM
- `vagrant halt` - Stop a VM
- `vagrant destroy` - Delete a VM
- `vagrant reload` - Restart a VM
- `vagrant provision` - Re-run provisioning
- `vagrant ssh` - Connect to VM via SSH
- `vagrant status` - Check VM status

## Development Process
1. Navigate to specific VM directory (e.g., `cd wordpressIAC`)
2. Run `vagrant up` to start the VM
3. Use `vagrant ssh` to connect and test
4. Make changes to Vagrantfile if needed
5. Run `vagrant reload --provision` to apply changes
6. Use `vagrant destroy` to clean up when done

## VM Management
- Each VM runs independently
- VMs can run simultaneously if resources allow
- Use different IP ranges to avoid conflicts
- Monitor resource usage with multiple VMs

## Troubleshooting
- Check VM status with `vagrant status`
- View logs with `vagrant up --debug`
- Connect to VM for manual troubleshooting
- Use `vagrant destroy && vagrant up` for clean rebuild

## Best Practices
- Test provisioning scripts thoroughly
- Use version control for Vagrantfiles
- Document VM purposes and configurations
- Keep VM configurations minimal and focused
- Clean up VMs when not in use

## Network Access
- WordPress VMs: Access via private IP (192.168.56.x)
- Finance VMs: Access via private IP (192.168.56.x)
- All VMs have public network access
- No port forwarding configured by default
